    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-04-19T08:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-04-19T08:40:00-05:00" n="143"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d143">
                <head>143. Telegram From the Commander of Special Task Group 81.8 (<persName
                        corresp="#p_CRAJE1" type="from">Clark</persName>) to the Commander in Chief,
                    Atlantic (<persName corresp="#p_DARL1" type="to">Dennison</persName>)<note n="0"
                        type="source" xml:id="d143fn0">Source: Naval Historical Center, Area Files,
                        Bumpy Road Materials. Top Secret. Repeated to <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                            >JCS</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <gloss target="#t_USS1">USS</gloss> Essex, Caribbean</placeName>, <date
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1961-04-19T08:40:00">April 19, 1961, 8:40
                            a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>191340Z. Exclusive for <persName corresp="#p_DARL1">Dennison</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_GMGDW1">Gray</persName>, from <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRAJE1">Clark</persName>. Bumpy Road. Your 190627Z.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d143fn1">
                        <ref target="#d137">Document 137</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>All evidence indicates <gloss target="#t_CEF1">CEF</gloss> ashore still
                        are organized fighting unit and not shifting to guerilla activity. Believe
                        one body of survivors from Red Reach attempting to join main body at Blue
                        Beach. Nothing was delivered to beach area by sea during the night.
                        Indications are that <gloss target="#t_CEF1">CEF</gloss> ashore is low on
                        all supplies, including <gloss target="#t_ammo1">ammo</gloss> and is hard
                        pressed if not desperate. Air drops by <gloss target="#t_CEF1">CEF</gloss>
                        planes poorly delivered. Most fall into sea.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>All above from intercepted <gloss target="#t_CEF1">CEF</gloss>
                        traffic.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>All this radio traffic is addressed for either action or <gloss
                            target="#t_info1">info</gloss> to Cdr. <persName>Millard</persName>ʼs
                        boss, who is the same as Col. <persName>Mallard</persName>ʼs boss.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
